        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-04-26T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-04-26T10:00:00-05:00" n="350" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d350">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.42700 (R)/4–2649: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kohler</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-04-26T18:00:00+03:00">April 26, 1949—6 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1054. <gloss target="#t_VOA1">VOA</gloss> Russian now totally jammed 1800 and
                    2100 GMT. New jammers began 2100 GMT April 24 blanking every frequency except
                    9700. April 25 all blanked. Airpouching recording <gloss target="#t_IBD1">IBD</gloss>. <gloss target="#t_BBC1">BBC</gloss> Russian also blanked.
                    Jammers of powerful type previously heard only against radio Madrid. See no hope
                    getting through by increase signal strength since jammers loud enough blank
                    radio Moscow itself.<note n="1" xml:id="d350fn1">The Embassy reported in
                        telegram 1063 from Moscow on April 27 that the jamming still continued, and
                        estimated that between 12 and 21 jammers were now available for simultaneous
                        operation in the Moscow area.</note> Urgent use more frequencies at once if
                    available in order retain listeners.<note n="2" xml:id="d350fn2">In reply to the
                        Embassy in telegram 272 on April 28 the Department advised that at present
                        it was technically impossible to increase the number of transmitters; but it
                        derived some satisfaction because the jamming would at least force the
                        Soviet Government to concentrate its “radio activity on jamming rather than
                        more productive projects.”</note>
                    <gloss target="#t_VOA1">VOA</gloss> by far our most important means direct
                    action Soviet people.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 1054, repeated Munich 2.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kohler</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
